{{Infobox language |name = Gbandi |nativename = |pronunciation = |states = [[Guinea]], [[Liberia]] |speakers = ca. 100,000 |date=2001 |ref=e18 |familycolor= Niger-Congo |fam1=[[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo]] |fam2 = [[Mande languages|Mande]] |fam3=Western Mande |fam4=[[Southwestern Mande languages|Southwestern]] |fam5=Mende–Loma |fam6=Mende–Bandi |fam7=Bandi–Zialo |iso3 = bza |glotto=band1352 |glottorefname=Bandi |dia1 = Tahamba |dia2 = Wawoma |dia3 = Vukoha |dia4 = Hasala |dia5 = Lukasu |dia6 = Hembeh |script = [[Latin script|Latin]] }}
The '''Bandi language''', also known as '''Bande''', '''Gbande''', '''Gbandi''' and '''Gbunde''', is a [[Mande language]]. It is spoken primarily in [[Lofa County]] in northern [[Liberia]] by the [[Gbandi people]].<ref name="Ethnologue, 16th ed"> {{cite web | url = http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=bza | title = Bandi | author = Lewis, M. Paul (ed.) | year = 2009 | work = [[Ethnologue|Ethnologue: Languages of the World, 16th edition]] | publisher = [[SIL International]] | location = [[Dallas]], [[Texas]] | accessdate = 3 October 2010 }}</ref>
Bandi has six [[dialect]]s: Hasala, Hembeh, Lukasa, Wawana, Wulukoha, and Tahamba, which is the dialect used for literature.<ref name="Ethnologue, 16th ed"/> The dialects have a [[lexical similarity]] of 96% among one another, and 83% with the most similar dialect of the [[Mende language]].<ref name="Ethnologue, 16th ed"/>
== See also == * [[Languages of Liberia]] The Gbandi language has the following dialects: Wawoma, Tahamba, Hembeh, Hassallah, Lukasu and Lukassu.
