{{for|the 2007 film|Juncture (film)}}
{{for|the British academic journal|Institute for Public Policy Research}}
'''Juncture''', in [[linguistics]], is the manner of moving (transition) or mode of relationship between two consecutive sounds.  It is the relationship between two successive [[syllable]]s in speech.{{sfn|Nicolosi|Harryman|Kresheck|2004|p=166}}  A juncture is, formally, a [[Segment (linguistics)|suprasegment]]al [[phoneme|phonem]]ic cue, a means by which a listener can distinguish between two otherwise identical sequences of sounds that have different meanings.{{sfn|Nicolosi|Harryman|Kresheck|2004|p=166}}

== Typology ==
There are several kinds of juncture, the most widely used typology of which is:
;plus juncture:Also known as '''open juncture''', this is subdivided into '''internal open juncture''' and '''external open juncture'''.  It is the juncture that occurs at word boundaries.{{sfn|Skandera|Burleigh|2011|p=62}}  In phonetic transcription open juncture is transcribed {{IPA|/+/}}, hence the name ''plus'' juncture.{{sfn|Skandera|Burleigh|2011|p=62}}
;close juncture:Also known as a '''normal transition''', this is a transition between segments (sounds) within a word.{{sfn|Skandera|Burleigh|2011|p=62}}
;terminal juncture:Also known as '''falling''',{{sfn|Crystal|2011|p=238}} '''clause terminal''' or '''terminal contour''',{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}} this is the juncture at the end of a clause or utterance with falling pitch before a silence.{{sfn|Crystal|2011|p=238}}

Other less common typologies exist,{{sfn|Skandera|Burleigh|2011|p=62}} such as the division (favoured by American [[Structural linguistics|Structuralist linguist]]s in the middle twentieth century) into '''plus''', '''single bar''', '''double bar''', and '''double cross''' junctures, denoted {{IPA|/+/}}, {{IPA|/{{!}}/}}, {{IPA|/{{!}}{{!}}/}}, and {{IPA|/#/}} respectively.{{sfn|Rajimwale|2006|pp=119–120}}{{sfn|Trask|1996|loc="double-bar juncture"}}{{sfn|Trask|1996|loc="double-cross juncture"}}  These correspond to syllabification and differences in intonation, single bar being a level pitch before a break, double bar being an upturn in pitch and a break, and double cross being a downturn in pitch that usually comes at the end of an utterance.{{sfn|Trask|1996|loc="double-bar juncture"}}{{sfn|Trask|1996|loc="double-cross juncture"}}{{sfn|Trask|1996|loc="single-bar juncture"}}{{sfn|Malmkjaer|2002|p=409}}

== Examples from English ==
In English, a syllable break at the plus juncture sometimes distinguishes otherwise homophonic phrases.

* "a name" {{IPAc-en|ə|.|n|eɪ|m}} and "an aim" {{IPAc-en|ən|.|eɪ|m}}{{sfn|Nasr|1997|p=45}}
* "that stuff" {{IPAc-en|ð|æ|t|.|s|t|ʌ|f}} and "that's tough" {{IPAc-en|ð|æ|t|s|.|t|ʌ|f}}{{sfn|Skandera|Burleigh|2011|p=62}}{{sfn|Rajimwale|2006|pp=119}}

A word boundary preceded or followed by a syllable break is called an ''external open juncture''. If there is no break, so that words on either side of the juncture are run together, the boundary is called an ''internal open juncture''.{{sfn|Skandera|Burleigh|2011|p=62}}

The distinction between open and close juncture is the difference between "[[wikt:night#English|night]] [[wikt:rate#English|rate]]", {{IPAc-en|n|aɪ|t|.|r|eɪ|t}} with the open juncture between {{IPAc-en|t}} and {{IPAc-en|r}}, and "[[wikt:nitrate#English|nitrate]]", {{IPAc-en|n|aɪ|.|t|r|eɪ|t}} with close juncture between {{IPAc-en|t}} and {{IPAc-en|r}}.{{sfn|Skandera|Burleigh|2011|p=62}} In some [[varieties of English]], only the latter involves an [[affricate]].

== Oronyms ==
In [[recreational linguistics]], an ''oronym'' is a pair of phrases which are [[homophone|homophonic]]. When pronounced without a pause between words (internal open juncture), phrases which differ in meaning and spelling may share a similar pronunciation. An example is "ice cream" {{IPA|/aɪs+kriːm/}} and "I scream" {{IPA|/aɪ+skriːm/}} (which is employed in the chant "I scream; you scream; we all scream for ice cream" that is familiar to many English-speaking children.{{sfn|Goldstein|2010|p=321}}). The label ''oronym'' was suggested by [[Gyles Brandreth]] and first published in his book ''The Joy of Lex'' (1980).
''[[The Two Ronnies]]'' comedy sketch "[[Four Candles]]" is entirely built around oronyms, including a taciturn customer's request for "fork handles" being misheard as "four candles."<ref>{{cite web|title=Four candles|url=https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=two+ronnies+four+candles|accessdate=28 Nov 2011}}</ref>

An older meaning of the word ''oronym'', used in the context of topographical nomenclature, is: [[toponym]] of a mountain.

